In this press briefing, White House Press Secretary Jay Carney, Chairman of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission Greg Jaczko, and Deputy Secretary of Energy Dan Poneman discuss the situation in Japan following the Fukushima nuclear disaster. They provide updates on the actions being taken by the US government to assist the Japanese in dealing with the crisis and the implications for American citizens. They also discuss the recommendations made by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission in response to the situation, such as the evacuation of citizens within a 50-mile radius of the Fukushima plant. The officials stress that there is no concern about harmful radiation levels in the US or its territories. They also address questions about the reliability of information being provided by the Japanese government and the safety of nuclear facilities in the US. The briefing concludes with comments on the situation in Libya and Bahrain.